{{IPA notice}}

This article is a technical description of the '''[[phonetics]] and [[phonology]] of [[Korean language|Korean]]'''. Unless otherwise noted, statements in this article refer to [[South Korean standard language]] based on the [[Gyeonggi dialect|Seoul dialect]].

[[Morphophoneme]]s are written inside vertical pipes ({{IPA|{{pipe}}&nbsp;{{pipe}}}}), [[phoneme]]s inside slashes ({{IPA|/&nbsp;/}}), and [[allophone]]s inside brackets ({{IPA|[&nbsp;]}}).

==Consonants==
Korean has 19 consonant phonemes.<ref name="Sohn">{{Cite book|title=Korean: Descriptive Grammar|last=Sohn|first=Ho-Min|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=1994|isbn=9780415003186|series=Descriptive Grammars|location=London|pages=432}}</ref>

For each stop and affricate, there is a three-way contrast between unvoiced segments, which are distinguished as '''plain''', '''tense''', and '''aspirated'''.
*The "plain" segments, sometimes referred to as "lax" or "lenis," are considered to be the more "basic" or unmarked members of the Korean obstruent series.
*The "tense" segments, also referred to as "fortis," "hard," or "glottalized," have eluded precise description and have been the subject of considerable phonetic investigation. In the [[Korean alphabet]] as well as all widely used [[Romanization of Korean|romanization systems for Korean]], they are represented as doubled plain segments: {{lang|ko|ㅃ}} {{transl|ko|pp}}, {{lang|ko|ㄸ}} {{transl|ko|tt}}, {{lang|ko|ㅉ}} {{transl|ko|jj}}, {{lang|ko|ㄲ}} {{transl|ko|kk}}. As it was suggested from the Middle Korean spelling, the tense consonants came from the initial consonant clusters ''sC''-, ''pC''-, ''psC''-.<ref name="Kim-Renaud">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nonRl2cerIgC&pg=PA169|title=The Korean Alphabet: Its History and Structure|publisher=[[University of Hawaiʻi Press]]|year=1997|isbn=9780824817237|editor-last=Kim-Renaud|editor-first=Young-Key|location=Honolulu|pages=169–170|language=English}}</ref><ref name="Brown_Yeon">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ALv7CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA38|title=The Handbook of Korean Linguistics|publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell]]|year=2015|isbn=9781118370933|location=West Sussex, UK|editor1-last=Brown|editor1-first=Lucien|editor2-last=Yeon|editor2-first=Jaehoon}}</ref>{{Rp|29, 38, 452}}
*The aspirated segments are characterized by [[aspirated consonant|aspiration]], a burst of air accompanied by the delayed [[Voice-onset time|onset of voicing]].
*The "plain" segments are also distinguished from the tense and aspirated phonemes by changes in vowel quality, including a relatively lower [[fundamental frequency|pitch]] of the following vowel.<ref name="Cho_Jun_Ladefoged">{{Cite journal|last=Cho|first=Taehong|last2=Jun|first2=Sun-Ah|last3=Ladefoged|first3=Peter|year=2002|title=Acoustic and aerodynamic correlates of Korean stops and fricatives|url=http://site.hanyang.ac.kr/documents/24916/113960/Cho_Jun_Ladefoged_2002_JPhon.pdf|journal=[[Journal of Phonetics]]|volume=30|issue=2|pages=193–228|doi=10.1006/jpho.2001.0153}}</ref>

