The [[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] diacritic {{angbr|{{IPA|◌͈}}}}, resembling a subscript double straight quotation mark, shown here with a placeholder circle, is used to denote the tensed consonants {{IPA|/p͈/, /t͈/, /k͈/, /t͈ɕ/, /s͈/}}.{{efn|Sometimes the tense consonants are marked with an apostrophe, {{angbr|{{IPA|ʼ}}}}, but that is not IPA usage; in the IPA, the apostrophe indicates [[ejective]] consonants.}} Its official use in the [[Extensions to the IPA]] is for [[Fortis and lenis|strong]] articulation, but is used in literature for [[faucalized voice]]. The Korean consonants also have elements of [[stiff voice]], but it is not yet{{When|date=May 2015}} known how typical that is of faucalized consonants. They are produced with a partially constricted [[glottis]] and additional subglottal pressure in addition to tense vocal tract walls, laryngeal lowering, or other expansion of the larynx.

An alternative analysis<ref name="Kim_San">{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Mi-Ryoung|last2=San|first2=Duanmu|year=2004|title='Tense' and 'Lax' Stops in Korean|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/262952103_Tense_and_Lax_Stops_in_Korean|journal=Journal of East Asian Linguistics|volume=13|issue=1|pages=59–104|doi=10.1023/B:JEAL.0000007344.43938.4e}}</ref> proposes that the "tensed" series of sounds are (fundamentally) regular voiceless, unaspirated consonants: the "lax" sounds are voiced consonants that become devoiced initially, and the primary distinguishing feature between word-initial "lax" and "tensed" consonants is that initial [[Lax vowel|lax]] sounds cause the following vowel to assume a low-to-high pitch contour, a feature reportedly associated with voiced consonants in many Asian languages, whereas tensed (and also aspirated) consonants are associated with a uniformly high pitch.

{{IPA|/p, t, tɕ, k/}} are voiced {{IPA|[b, d, dʑ, ɡ]}} between voiced sounds but voiceless elsewhere. Among younger generations, they may be just as aspirated as {{IPA|/pʰ, tʰ, tɕʰ, kʰ/}} in initial position; the primary difference is that the following vowel carries a low tone.<ref name="Kim_Beddor_Horrocks">{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Mi-Ryoung|last2=Beddor|first2=Patrice Speeter|last3=Horrocks|first3=Julie|year=2002|title=The contribution of consonantal and vocalic information to the perception of Korean initial stops|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0095447001901524|journal=[[Journal of Phonetics]]|volume=30|issue=1|pages=77–100|doi=10.1006/jpho.2001.0152}}</ref><ref name="Lee-K_Ramsey">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.kr/books?id=2AmspKX3beoC&pg=PA293|title=A History of the Korean Language|last=Lee|first=Ki-Moon|last2=Ramsey|first2=S. Robert|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=2011|isbn=9780521661898|location=Cambridge|pages=293}}</ref> {{IPA|/pʰ, tʰ, tɕʰ, kʰ/}} are strongly aspirated, more so than English voiceless stops. The affricates {{IPA|/tɕ͈, tɕʰ, tɕ/}} may be pronounced as alveolar ({{IPA|[ts͈, tsʰ, ts~dz]}} by some speakers, especially before back vowels.

The analysis of {{IPA|/s/}} as phonologically plain or aspirated has been a source of controversy in the literature.<ref name="Chang">{{Cite journal|last=Chang|first=Charles B.|year=2013|title=The production and perception of coronal fricatives in Seoul Korean: The case for a fourth laryngeal category|url=http://eprints.soas.ac.uk/18997/1/Chang_KL15.pdf|journal=Korean Linguistics|volume=15|issue=1|pages=7–49|doi=10.1075/kl.15.1.02cha}}</ref> Its characteristics are nearest to those of plain stops, as it generally undergoes intervocalic voicing word-medially.<ref name="Cho_Jun_Ladefoged" /> It shows moderate aspiration word-initially, but no aspiration word-medially.<ref name="Cho_Jun_Ladefoged" /> {{IPA|/s, s͈/}} are palatalized {{IPA|[ɕ, ɕ͈]}} before {{IPA|/i, j/}}.

{{IPA|/m, n/}} tend to be [[denasalization|denasalized]] word-initially.<ref name="Kim">{{Cite thesis|last=Kim|first=Young Shin|title=An acoustic, aerodynamic and perceptual investigation of word-initial denasalization in Korean|date=2011|degree=Doctoral|publisher=[[University College London]]|url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/id/eprint/1324541}}</ref> {{IPA|/ŋ/}} appears only between vowels and in the syllable coda.

{{IPA|/l/}} is an alveolar flap {{IPA|[ɾ]}} between vowels or between a vowel and an {{IPA|/h/}}; it is {{IPA|[l]}} or {{IPA|[ɭ]}} at the end of a word, before a consonant other than {{IPA|/h/}}, or next to another {{IPA|/l/}}. There is free variation at the beginning of a word, where this phoneme tends to become {{IPA|[n]}} before most vowels and silent before {{IPA|/i, j/}}, but it is commonly {{IPA|[ɾ]}} in English loanwords.

Between vowels, {{IPA|/h/}} may either be voiced to {{IPA|[ɦ]}} or deleted.

=== Positional allophones ===
Korean consonants have three principal positional allophones: initial, medial (voiced), and final (checked). The initial form is found at the beginning of [[phonological word]]s. The medial form is found in voiced environments, intervocalically and after a voiced consonant such as {{transl|ko|n}} or {{transl|ko|l}}. The final form is found in checked environments such as at the end of a phonological word or before an obstruent consonant such as {{transl|ko|t}} or {{transl|ko|k}}. Nasal consonants ({{transl|ko|m}}, {{transl|ko|n}}, {{transl|ko|ng}}) do not have noticeable positional allophones beyond initial denasalization, and {{transl|ko|ng}} cannot appear in this position.

