All [[obstruent]]s (stops, affricates, fricatives) become stops with [[no audible release]] at the end of a word: all coronals collapse to {{IPA|[t̚]}}, all labials to {{IPA|[p̚]}}, and all velars to {{IPA|[k̚]}}.{{efn|The only fortis consonants to occur finally are {{lang|ko|ㄲ}} {{transl|ko|kk}} and {{lang|ko|ㅆ}} {{transl|ko|ss}}.}} Final {{lang|ko|ㄹ}} {{transl|ko|r}} is a [[Lateral consonant|lateral]] {{IPA|[l]}} or {{IPA|[ɭ]}}.

{{lang|ko|ㅎ}} {{transl|ko|h}} does not occur in final position,{{efn|Orthographically, it is found at the end of the name of the letter {{lang|ko|ㅎ}}, {{lang|ko|히읗}} {{transl|ko|hieut}}.}} though it does occur at the end of non-final syllables, where it affects the following consonant. (See below.) Intervocalically, it is realized as voiced {{IPA|[ɦ]}}, and after voiced consonants it is either {{IPA|[ɦ]}} or silent.

{{lang|ko|ㅇ}} {{transl|ko|ng}} does not occur in initial position, reflected in the way the hangeul jamo {{lang|ko|ㅇ}} has a different pronunciation in the initial position to the final position. These were distinguished when hangeul was created, with the jamo {{lang|ko|ㆁ}} with the upper dot and the jamo {{lang|ko|ㅇ}} without the upper dot; these were then conflated and merged in the standards for both the North Korean and South Korean standards. 

In native Korean words, {{lang|ko|ㄹ}} {{transl|ko|r}} does not occur word initially, unlike in Chinese loans ([[Sino-Korean vocabulary]]). In South Korea, it is silent in initial position before {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/j/}}, pronounced {{IPA|[n]}} before other vowels, and pronounced {{IPA|[ɾ]}} only in compound words after a vowel. The prohibition on word-initial {{transl|ko|r}} is called the "initial law" or {{transl|ko|[[dueum beopchik]]}} ({{lang|ko|두음법칙}}). Initial {{transl|ko|r}} is officially pronounced {{IPA|[ɾ]}} in North Korea. In both countries, initial {{transl|ko|r}} in words of foreign origin other than Chinese is pronounced {{IPA|[ɾ]}}.

* "labour" ({{lang|ko|勞動}}) – North Korea: {{transl|ko|'''r'''odong}} ({{lang|ko|로동}}), South Korea: {{transl|ko|'''n'''odong}} ({{lang|ko|노동}})
* "history" ({{lang|ko|歷史}}) – North Korea: {{transl|ko|'''ry'''ŏksa}} ({{lang|ko|력사}}), South Korea: {{transl|ko|'''y'''eoksa}} ({{lang|ko|역사}})

This rule also extends to {{lang|ko|ㄴ}} {{transl|ko|n}} in many native and all Sino-Korean words, which is also lost before initial {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/j/}} in South Korean; again, North Korean preserves the {{IPA|[n]}} phoneme there. 

* "female" ({{lang|ko|女子}}) – North Korea: {{transl|ko|'''ny'''ŏja}} ({{lang|ko|녀자}}), South Korea: {{transl|ko|'''y'''eoja}} ({{lang|ko|여자}})

==Vowels==
{{Update section|date=February 2017}}
{{multiple image
|align=right
|direction=vertical
|width=250
|image1=Korean short vowel chart.svg
|image2=Korean long vowel chart.svg
|footer=The vowel phonemes of Korean on a [[vowel chart]], from (Lee, 1999).<ref name="Lee" /> The bottom chart represents long vowels.
}}

Korean has eight vowel phonemes and a length distinction for each. Long vowels are pronounced somewhat more peripherally than short ones. Two more vowels, the [[mid front rounded vowel]] ({{IPAblink|ø̞|ø}} {{lang|ko|ㅚ}}) and the [[close front rounded vowel]] ({{IPAblink|y}} {{lang|ko|ㅟ}}),<ref name="Ahn_Iverson">{{Cite book|url=http://www.jbe-platform.com/content/books/9789027292162|title=Historical Linguistics 2005|last=Ahn|first=Sang-Cheol|last2=Iverson|first2=Gregory K.|publisher=[[John Benjamins]]|year=2005|isbn=9789027247995|editor-last=Salmons|editor-first=Joseph C.|location=Madison, WI|pages=275–293|chapter=Structured imbalances in the emergence of the Korean vowel system|doi=10.1075/cilt.284.21ahn|editor-last2=Dubenion-Smith|editor-first2=Shannon|chapter-url=http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download;jsessionid=58DB2341AD27B2A08777AA5ABBB8266F?doi=10.1.1.557.3316&rep=rep1&type=pdf}}</ref>{{Rp|6}} can still be heard in the speech of some older speakers, but they have been largely replaced by the diphthongs {{IPA|[we]}} and {{IPA|[ɥi]}}, respectively.<ref name="Brown_Yeon" />{{Rp|4–6}} In a 2003 survey of 350 speakers from Seoul, nearly 90% pronounced the vowel {{lang|ko|ㅟ}} as {{IPA|[ɥi]}}.<ref name="Lee-I_Ramsey">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NN-yIdLOkCoC&pg=PA66|title=The Korean Language|last=Lee|first=Iksop|last2=Ramsey|first2=S. Robert|publisher=[[SUNY Press]]|year=2000|isbn=0791448312|location=Albany, NY|pages=66}}</ref>

In 2012, vowel length is reported almost completely neutralized in Korean, except for a very few older speakers of Seoul dialect,<ref name="Kim-Renaud_Tranter">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.kr/books?id=I7PTXPq_nSAC&pg=PA127|title=The Languages of Japan and Korea|last=Kim-Renaud|first=Young-Key|publisher=[[Routledge]]|year=2012|isbn=9780415462877|editor-last=Tranter|editor-first=Nicolas|location=Oxon, UK|pages=127}}</ref> for whom the distinctive vowel-length distinction is maintained only in the first syllable of a word.<ref name="Lee-I_Ramsey" />

The distinction between {{IPA|/e/}} and {{IPA|/ɛ/}} is lost in South Korean dialects but robust in North Korean dialects.<ref name="Kwak">{{Cite journal|last=Kwak|first=Chung-gu|year=2003|title=The Vowel System of Contemporary Korean and Direction of Change|url=http://www.dbpia.co.kr/Article/NODE00922107|journal=Journal of Korea Linguistics|volume=41|pages=59–91}}</ref><ref name="Kang_Schertz_Han">{{Cite journal|last=Kang|first=Yoonjung|last2=Schertz|first2=Jessamyn L.|last3=Han|first3=Sungwoo|year=2015|title=Vowels of Korean dialects|url=http://asa.scitation.org/doi/abs/10.1121/1.4920798|journal=[[Journal of the Acoustical Society of America]]|volume=137|issue=4|pages=2414–2414|doi=10.1121/1.4920798}}</ref> For the speakers who do not make the difference, {{IPA|[e̞]}} seems to be the dominant form.<ref name="Brown_Yeon" />{{Rp|4–6}} For most of the speakers who still utilize vowel length contrastively, long {{IPA|/ʌː/}} is actually {{IPA|[ɘː]}}.<ref name="Lee">{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/rosettaproject_kor_phon-2|title=Handbook of the International Phonetic Association: A Guide to the Use of the International Phonetic Alphabet|last=Lee|first=Hyun Bok|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=1999|isbn=9780521637510|location=Cambridge|pages=120–123|chapter=Korean}}</ref> In [[Gyeonggi dialect|Seoul Korean]], {{IPA|/o/}} is produced higher than {{IPA|/ʌ/}}, while in [[Pyongan dialect|Pyongan]], {{IPA|/o/}} is lower than {{IPA|/ʌ/}}.<ref name="Kang_Schertz_Han" /> In [[Hamgyŏng dialect|Northeastern Korean]] tonal dialect, the two are comparable in height and the main contrast is along pitch.<ref name="Kang_Schertz_Han" /> Within Seoul Korean, {{IPA|/o/}} is raised toward {{IPA|/u/}} while {{IPA|/ɯ/}} is fronted away from {{IPA|/u/}} in younger speakers’ speech.<ref name="Kang_Schertz_Han" />

[[Middle Korean language|Middle Korean]] had an additional vowel phoneme denoted by {{lang|ko|ᆞ}}, known as {{transl|ko|arae-a}} (literally "lower a"). The vowel merged with {{IPAblink|a}} in all mainland varieties of Korean but remains distinct in [[Jeju language|Jeju]], where it is pronounced {{IPAblink|ɒ}}.

