In current pronunciation, {{IPA|/ɰi/}} merges into {{IPA|/i/}} after a consonant.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} Some analyses treat {{IPA|/ɯ/}} as a central vowel and thus the marginal sequence {{IPA|/ɰi/}} as having a central-vowel onset, which would be more accurately transcribed {{IPA|[ȷ̈i]}} or {{IPA|[ɨ̯i]}}.<ref name="Ahn_Iverson" />{{Rp|12}}

Modern Korean has no [[falling diphthong]]s, with sequences like {{IPA|/a.i/}} being considered as two separate vowels in [[hiatus (linguistics)|hiatus]]. Middle Korean had a full set of diphthongs ending in {{IPA|/j/}}, which monophthongized into the front vowels in Early Modern Korean ({{IPA|/aj/ > /ɛ/}}, {{IPA|/əj/ [ej] > /e/}}, {{IPA|/oj/ > /ø/}}, {{IPA|/uj/ > /y/}}, {{IPA|/ɯj/ > /ɰi ~ i/}}).<ref name="Ahn_Iverson" />{{Rp|12}} This is the reason why the hangul letters {{lang|ko|ㅐ}}, {{lang|ko|ㅔ}}, {{lang|ko|ㅚ}} and so on are represented as back vowels plus {{transl|ko|i}}.

== Assimilation ==

=== Vowel assimilation ===

The vowel that most affects consonants is {{IPA|/i/}}, which, along with its semivowel homologue {{IPA|/j/}}, palatalizes {{IPA|/s/}} and {{IPA|/s͈/}} to [[alveolo-palatal consonant|alveolo-palatal]] {{IPA|[ɕ]}} and {{IPA|[ɕ͈]}} for most speakers (but see [[differences in the language between North Korea and South Korea]]). As noted above, initial {{IPA|{{pipe}}l{{pipe}}}} is silent in this palatalizing environment, at least in South Korea. Similarly, an underlying {{IPA|{{pipe}}t{{pipe}}}} or {{IPA|{{pipe}}tʰ{{pipe}}}} at the ''end'' of a morpheme becomes a phonemically palatalized affricate {{IPA|/tɕʰ/}} when followed by a word or suffix beginning with {{IPA|/i/}} or {{IPA|/j/}} (it becomes indistinguishable from an underlying {{IPA|{{pipe}}tɕʰ{{pipe}}}}), but that does not happen within native Korean words such as {{IPA|/ʌti/}} {{IPA|[ʌdi]}} "where?".

{{IPA|/kʰ/}} is more affected by vowels, often becoming an affricate when followed by {{IPA|/i/}} or {{IPA|/ɯ/}}: {{IPA|[cçi]}}, {{IPA|[kxɯ]}}. The most variable consonant is {{IPA|/h/}}, which becomes a [[palatal consonant|palatal]] {{IPA|[ç]}} before {{IPA|/i/}} or {{IPA|/j/}}, a [[velar consonant|velar]] {{IPA|[x]}} before {{IPA|/ɯ/}}, and a [[bilabial consonant|bilabial]] {{IPA|[ɸʷ]}} before {{IPA|/o/}}, {{IPA|/u/}} and {{IPA|/w/}}.<ref name="Shin_Kiaer_Cha">{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.com/Sounds-Korean-Professor-Jiyoung-Shin/dp/1107672686|title=The Sounds of Korean|last=Shin|first=Jiyoung|last2=Kiaer|first2=Jieun|last3=Cha|first3=Jaeeun|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=2012|isbn=9781107672680|location=Cambridge|pages=77}}</ref>

