In many morphological processes, a vowel {{IPA|/i/}} before another vowel may become the semivowel {{IPA|/j/}}. Likewise,{{IPA|/u/}} and {{IPA|/o/}}, before another vowel, may reduce to {{IPA|/w/}}. In some dialects and speech registers, the semivowel {{IPA|/w/}} assimilates into a following {{IPA|/e/}} or {{IPA|/i/}} and produces the front rounded vowels {{IPA|[ø]}} and {{IPA|[y]}}.

=== Consonant assimilation ===
As noted above, [[Tenuis consonant|tenuis]] stops and {{IPA|/h/}} are voiced after the voiced consonants {{IPA|/m, n, ŋ, l/}}, and the resulting voiced {{IPA|[ɦ]}} tends to be elided. Tenuis stops become fortis after obstruents (which, as noted above, are reduced to {{IPA|[k̚, t̚, p̚]}}); that is, {{IPA|/kt/}} is pronounced {{IPA|[k̚t͈]}}. Fortis and nasal stops are unaffected by either environment, though {{IPA|/n/}} assimilates to {{IPA|/l/}} after an {{IPA|/l/}}. After {{IPA|/h/}}, tenuis stops become aspirated, {{IPA|/s/}} becomes fortis, and {{IPA|/n/}} is unaffected.{{efn|Other consonants do not occur after {{IPA|/h/}}, which is uncommon in morpheme-final position.}} {{IPA|/l/}} is highly affected: it becomes {{IPA|[n]}} after all consonants but {{IPA|/n/}} (which assimilates to the {{IPA|/l/}} instead) or another {{IPA|/l/}}. For example, underlying {{IPA|{{pipe}}tɕoŋlo{{pipe}}}} is pronounced {{IPA|/tɕoŋno/}}.<ref name="NHK">{{Cite book|title=ハングル入門|last=梅田|first=博之|publisher=NHK Publishing|year=1985|isbn=9784140350287|location=Tokyo}}</ref>

These are all ''progressive'' assimilation. Korean also has regressive (anticipatory) assimilation: a consonant tends to assimilate in [[manner of articulation|manner]] but not in [[place of articulation]]: Obstruents become nasal stops before nasal stops (which, as just noted, includes underlying {{IPA|{{pipe}}l{{pipe}}}}), but do not change their position in the mouth. Velar stops (that is, all consonants pronounced {{IPA|[k̚]}} in final position) become {{IPA|[ŋ]}}; coronals ({{IPA|[t̚]}}) become {{IPA|[n]}}, and labials ({{IPA|[p̚]}}) become {{IPA|[m]}}. For example, {{IPA|{{pipe}}hanku'''k'''mal{{pipe}}}} is pronounced {{IPA|/hanku'''ŋ'''mal/}} (phonetically {{IPA|[hanɡuŋmal]}}).<ref name="NHK" />

Before the fricatives {{IPA|/s, s͈/}}, coronal obstruents assimilate to a fricative, resulting in a [[geminate]]. That is, {{IPA|{{pipe}}tʰs{{pipe}}}} is pronounced {{IPA|/ss͈/}} ({{IPA|[s͈ː]}}).  A final {{IPA|/h/}} assimilates in both place and manner, so that {{IPA|{{pipe}}h[[consonant|C]]{{pipe}}}} is pronounced as a geminate (and, as noted above, aspirated if C is a stop). The two coronal sonorants, {{IPA|/n/}} and {{IPA|/l/}}, in whichever order, assimilate to {{IPA|/l/}}, so that both {{IPA|{{pipe}}nl{{pipe}}}} and {{IPA|{{pipe}}ln{{pipe}}}} are pronounced {{IPA|[lː]}}.<ref name="NHK" />

There are lexical exceptions to these generalizations. For example, voiced consonants occasionally cause a following consonant to become fortis rather than voiced; this is especially common with {{IPA|{{pipe}}ls{{pipe}}}} and {{IPA|{{pipe}}ltɕ{{pipe}}}} as {{IPA|[ls͈]}} and {{IPA|[lt͈ɕ]}}, but is also occasionally seen with other sequences, such as {{IPA|{{pipe}}kjʌ.u'''lp'''aŋhak{{pipe}}}} ({{IPA|[kjʌu'''lp͈'''aŋak̚]}}), {{IPA|{{pipe}}tɕʰa'''mt'''oŋan{{pipe}}}} ({{IPA|[tɕʰa'''mt͈'''oŋan]}}) and {{IPA|{{pipe}}weja'''ŋk'''anɯlo{{pipe}}}} ({{IPA|[weja'''ŋk͈'''anɯɾo]}}).<ref name="NHK" />

