# Velar obstruents found in final position: {{lang|ko|ㄱ}} {{transl|ko|g}}, {{lang|ko|ㄲ}} {{transl|ko|kk}}, {{lang|ko|ㅋ}} {{transl|ko|k}}
# Final coronal obstruents: {{lang|ko|ㄷ}} {{transl|ko|d}}, {{lang|ko|ㅌ}} {{transl|ko|t}}, {{lang|ko|ㅅ}} {{transl|ko|s}}, {{lang|ko|ㅆ}} {{transl|ko|ss}}, {{lang|ko|ㅈ}} {{transl|ko|j}}, {{lang|ko|ㅊ}} {{transl|ko|ch}}
# Final labial obstruents: {{lang|ko|ㅂ}} {{transl|ko|b}}, {{lang|ko|ㅍ}} {{transl|ko|p}}

The resulting geminate obstruents, such as {{IPA|[k̚k͈]}}, {{IPA|[ss͈]}}, {{IPA|[p̚pʰ]}}, and {{IPA|[t̚tɕʰ]}} (that is, {{IPA|[k͈ː]}}, {{IPA|[s͈ː]}}, {{IPA|[pʰː]}}, and {{IPA|[tːɕʰ]}}), tend to reduce ({{IPA|[k͈]}}, {{IPA|[s͈]}}, {{IPA|[pʰ]}}, {{IPA|[tɕʰ]}}) in rapid conversation. Heterorganic obstruent sequences such as {{IPA|[k̚p͈]}} and {{IPA|[t̚kʰ]}} may, less frequently, assimilate to geminates ({{IPA|[p͈ː]}}, {{IPA|[kːʰ]}}) and also reduce ({{IPA|[p͈]}}, {{IPA|[kʰ]}}).

These sequences assimilate with following vowels the way single consonants do, so that for example {{IPA|{{pipe}}ts{{pipe}}}} and {{IPA|{{pipe}}hs{{pipe}}}} palatalize to {{IPA|[ɕɕ͈]}} (that is, {{IPA|[ɕ͈ː]}}) before {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/j/}}; {{IPA|{{pipe}}hk{{pipe}}}} and {{IPA|{{pipe}}lkʰ{{pipe}}}} affricate to {{IPA|[kx]}} and {{IPA|[lkx]}} before {{IPA|/ɯ/}}; {{IPA|{{pipe}}ht{{pipe}}}}, {{IPA|{{pipe}}s͈h{{pipe}}}}, and {{IPA|{{pipe}}th{{pipe}}}} palatalize to {{IPA|[t̚tɕʰ]}} and {{IPA|[tɕʰ]}} across morpheme boundaries, and so on.

[[Hangul]] orthography does not generally reflect these assimilatory processes, but rather maintains the underlying [[morphology (linguistics)|morphology]] in most cases.

==Phonotactics==

Korean syllable structure is maximally /CGVC/, where /G/ is a glide {{IPA|/j, w, ɰ/}}. Any consonant except {{IPA|/ŋ/}} may occur initially, but only {{IPA|/p, t, k, m, n, ŋ, l/}} may occur finally. Sequences of two consonants may occur between vowels, as outlined above. However, morphemes may also end in CC [[consonant cluster|clusters]], which are  both expressed only when they are followed by a vowel. When the morpheme is not suffixed, one of the consonants is not expressed; if there is a {{IPA|/h/}}, which cannot appear in final position, it will be that. Otherwise it will be a coronal consonant (with the exception of ㄼ), and if the sequence is two coronals, the voiceless one ({{IPA|/s, tʰ, tɕ/}}) will drop, and {{IPA|/n/}} or {{IPA|/l/}} will remain. Thus, no sequence reduces to {{IPA|[t̚]}} in final position.

