|}

Traditionally, the Korean language has had strong [[vowel harmony]]; that is, in pre-modern Korean, not only did the inflectional and derivational affixes (such as [[postposition]]s) change in accordance to the main root vowel, but native words also adhered to vowel harmony.  It is not as prevalent in modern usage, although it remains strong in [[onomatopoeia]], [[adjective]]s and [[adverb]]s, [[interjection]]s, and [[Grammatical conjugation|conjugation]]. There are also other traces of vowel harmony in Korean.

There are three classes of vowels in Korean: positive, negative, and neutral. The vowel {{lang|ko|ㅡ}} (eu) is considered partially a neutral and negative vowel. The vowel classes loosely follow the negative and positive vowels; they also follow orthography. Exchanging positive vowels with negative vowels usually creates different nuances of meaning, with positive vowels sounding diminutive and negative vowels sounding crude:

*'''Onomatopoeia:'''
** {{lang|ko|퐁당퐁당}} ({{transl|ko|p'''o'''ngd'''a'''ng-p'''o'''ngd'''a'''ng}}) and {{lang|ko|풍덩풍덩}} ({{transl|ko|p'''u'''ngd'''eo'''ng-p'''u'''ngd'''eo'''ng}}), light and heavy water splashing
*'''Emphasised adjectives:'''
** {{lang|ko|노랗다}} ({{transl|ko|n'''o'''r'''a'''ta}}) means plain yellow, while its negative, {{lang|ko|누렇다}} ({{transl|ko|n'''u'''r'''eo'''ta}}) means very yellow
** {{lang|ko|파랗다}} ({{transl|ko|p'''a'''r'''a'''ta}}) means plain blue, while its negative, {{lang|ko|퍼렇다}} ({{transl|ko|p'''eo'''r'''eo'''ta}}) means deep blue
*'''Particles at the end of verbs:'''
** {{lang|ko|잡다}} ({{transl|ko|j'''a'''pda}}) (to catch) → {{lang|ko|잡았다}} ({{transl|ko|j'''a'''b'''a'''tda}}) (caught)
** {{lang|ko|접다}} ({{transl|ko|j'''eo'''pda}}) (to fold) → {{lang|ko|접었다}} ({{transl|ko|j'''eo'''b'''eo'''tda}}) (folded)
*'''Interjections:'''
** {{lang|ko|아이고}} ({{transl|ko|'''a'''ig'''o'''}}) and {{lang|ko|어이구}} ({{transl|ko|'''eo'''ig'''u'''}}) expressing surprise, discomfort or sympathy
** {{lang|ko|아하}} ({{transl|ko|'''a'''h'''a'''}}) and {{lang|ko|어허}} ({{transl|ko|'''eo'''h'''eo'''}}) expressing sudden realization and mild objection, respectively

== Dialectal pitch accents ==
Several dialects outside Seoul retain the Middle Korean [[pitch accent]] system. In the [[Gyeongsang dialect|dialect of Northern Gyeongsang]], in southeastern South Korea, any syllable may have pitch accent in the form of a high tone, as may the two initial syllables. For example, in trisyllabic words, there are four possible tone patterns:<ref name="Jun_Kim_Lee_Jun">{{Cite journal|last=Jun|first=Jongho|last2=Kim|first2=Jungsun|last3=Lee|first3=Hayoung|last4=Jun|first4=Sun-Ah|year=2006|title=The prosodic structure and pitch accent of Northern Kyungsang Korean|url=http://ling.snu.ac.kr/jun/work/JEAL_final.pdf|journal=Journal of East Asian Linguistics|volume=15|issue=4|pages=289–317|doi=10.1007/s10831-006-9000-2}}</ref>
*{{lang|ko|메누리}} {{transl|ko|ménuri}} {{IPA|[mé.nu.ɾi]}} 'daughter-in-law'
*{{lang|ko|어무이}} {{transl|ko|eomú-i}} {{IPA|[ʌ.mú.i]}} 'mother'
*{{lang|ko|원어민}} {{transl|ko|woneomín}} {{IPA|[wʌ.nʌ.mín]}} 'native speaker'
*{{lang|ko|오래비}} {{transl|ko|órébi}} {{IPA|[ó.ɾé.bi]}} 'elder brother'

