__NOTOC__ {{Infobox book | name = The Prisoner of the Caucasus | author = [[Alexander Pushkin]] | language = [[Russian language|Russian]] | country = [[Russian Empire]] | genre = [[Narrative poetry|Narrative poem]] | title_orig = Кавказский пленник |orig_lang_code= ru | translator = Roger Clarke | release_date = 1822 | media_type = Print }} '''''The Prisoner of the Caucasus''''' ({{lang-ru|«Кавказский пленник»}} ''Kavkázskiy plénnik''), also translated as '''''Captive of the Caucasus''''', is a [[narrative poetry|narrative poem]] written by [[Alexander Pushkin]] in 1820-21 and published in 1822. Dedicated to his friend General [[Nikolay Raevsky]], it was inspired by the poet's time spent in [[Pyatigorsk]] during his southern exile.<ref>{{cite book|last=Layton|first=Susan|title=Russian Literature and Empire: Conquest of the Caucasus from Pushkin to Tolstoy|location=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1995|page=26|isbn=978-0521444439}}</ref>
The poem is about a [[Byronic hero|Byronic]] Russian officer who is disillusioned with elite life and decides to escape by seeking adventure in the [[Caucasus]]. He is captured by [[Circassians|Circassian]] tribesmen but then saved by a [[Circassian beauties|beautiful Circassian woman]]. Despite its [[Romanticism|Romantic]] and [[Orientalism|Orientalist]] themes, Pushkin's use of academic footnotes and reliable ethnographic material gave it credibility in its day.<ref>Layton, p. 28</ref> It was highly influential on popular perceptions of the Caucasus for its time.<ref>{{cite book|last=King|first=Charles|authorlink=Charles King (professor of international affairs)|title=The Ghost of Freedom: A History of the Caucasus|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0195177756|pages=110-112}}</ref> The poem remains one of Pushkin's most famous works and is often referenced in [[Russian culture|Russian popular culture]], in films such as the Soviet comedy ''[[Kidnapping, Caucasian Style]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russian Film: 'Кавказская Пленница' – 'Kidnapping, Caucasian Style'|url=http://ruslanguage.ru/blog/russian-film-%D0%BA%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%BA%D0%B0%D0%B7%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B0%D1%8F-%D0%BF%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D0%B8%D1%86%D0%B0-kidnapping-caucasian-style/|work=Ruslanguage School|accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref>
==English translations== * Roger Clarke, in {{cite book|title=Eugene Onegin & Other Stories|location=London|publisher=Wordsworth Editions|year=2005|isbn=978-1840221367}}
